08773nam a22010095i 9781846159442DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20112011xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97818461594427 a10.1515/97818461594422doi  a(DE-B1597)675861  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aCC135b.C85 2011eb 7aSOC0030002bisacsh04a363.6922200aCultural Heritage, Ethics, and the Military /ced. by Peter G. Stone. 1aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b11 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHeritage Matters ;v400tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tList of abbreviations -- tIntroduction: The Ethical Challenges for Cultural Heritage Experts Working with the Military -- t1 Still in the Aftermath of Waterloo: A Brief History of Decisions about Restitution -- t2 Physicians at War: Lessons for Archaeologists? -- t3 Christian Responsibility and the Preservation of Civilisation in Wartime: George Bell and the Fate of Germany in World War II -- t4 Responding to Culture in Conflict -- t5 How Academia and the Military can Work Together -- t6 Archaeologist under Pressure: Neutral or Cooperative in Wartime -- t7 Ancient Artefacts and Modern Conflict: A Case Study of Looting and Instability in Iraq -- t8 Whose Heritage? Archaeology, Heritage and the Military -- t9 Military Archaeology in the US: A Complex Ethical Decision -- t10 Akwesasne – Where the Partridges Drum to Fort Drum: Consultation with Native Communities, an Evolving Process -- t11 Heritage Resources and Armed Conflicts: An African Perspective -- t12 Human Shields: Social Scientists on Point in Modern Asymmetrical Conflicts -- t13 Politicians: Assassins of Lebanese Heritage? Archaeology in Lebanon in Times of Armed Conflict -- t14 Relations between Archaeologists and the Military in the Case of Iraq: Foreword -- tRelations between Archaeologists and the Military in the Case of Iraq -- tResponses to ‘Relations between Archaeologists and the Military in the Case of Iraq’ -- tRelations between Archaeologists and the Military in the Case of Iraq – Reply to Price, Rowlands, Rush, and Teijgeler -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExamines the ethical dilemma of whether, and how, archaeologists and other experts should work with the military to protect cultural property in times of conflict.The world reacted with horror to the images of the looting of the National Museum in Iraq in 2003 - closely followed by other museums and then, largely unchecked, or archaeological sites across the country. This outcome had been predicted by many archaeologists, with some offering to work directly with the military to identify museums and sites to be avoided and protected. However, this work has since been heavily criticised by others working in the field,who claim that such collaboration lended a legitimacy to the invasion. It has therefore served to focus on the broader issue of whether archaeologists and other cultural heritage experts should ever work with the military,and, if so, under what guidelines and strictures. The essays in this book, drawn from a series of international conferences and seminars on the debate, provide an historical background to the ethical issues facing cultural heritage experts, and place them in a wider context. How do medical and religious experts justify their close working relationships with the military? Is all contact with those engaged in conflict wrong? Does working with the military really constitute tacit agreement with military and political goals, or can it be seen as contributing to the winning of a peace rather than success in war? Are guidelines required to help define roles and responsibilities? And can conflict situations be seen as simply an extension of protecting cultural property on military training bases? The book opens and addresses these and other questions as matters of crucial debate. Contributors: Peter Stone, Margaret M. Miles, Fritz Allhoff, Andrew Chandler, Oliver Urquhart Irvine, Barney White-Spunner, René Teijgeler, Katharyn Hanson, Martin Brown, Laurie Rush, Francis Scardera, Caleb Adebayo Folorunso, Derek Suchard, Joanne Farchakh Bajjaly, John Curtis, Jon Price, Mike Rowlands, Iain Shearer  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArchaeologyxPhilosophy. 0aCivil-military relationsvCase studies. 0aClassical antiquitiesxDestruction and pillage. 0aCultural propertyxProtectionxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aCultural propertyxProtection. 0aIraq War, 2003-2011xDestruction and pillage. 0aMilitary occupationxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPillage. 4aArchaeology & Heritage. 4aHistory of Religion. 4aModern History. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh  aarchaeologists.  aconflict.  acultural heritage experts.  acultural property.  aethics.  ainvasion.  amedical experts.  amilitary training bases.  amilitary.  areligious experts.1 aAdebayo Folorunso, Caleb, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAllhoff, Fritz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChandler, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurtis, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarchakh Bajjally, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarchakh Bajjaly, Joanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFolorunso, Caleb Adebayo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators